      "content": "but the 'practical' explanation doesn't account for the way the lines don't just center on the buildings, but actually point toward them from hundreds of miles away, like they're part of a larger, global geometry. if you look at the way the radial patterns in london connect to the gridlines in nyc, it's not just about 'prominence,' it's like there's a hidden blueprint being used to anchor these financial centers to specific geometric nodes. if this pattern holds up across other major cities, doesn't it suggest that the planning isn't just about economics, but about maintaining a specific structural alignment across the whole network?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
